    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#ghislanzoni1915"/>, p. <citedRange>175</citedRange></bibl>, whence 
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SEG"/>, <citedRange>9.249</citedRange></bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>029300</citedRange></bibl>.
                    Cf. <bibl><ptr target="#thorn2005"/>, p. 422, n. <citedRange>ii </citedRange>and fig. 257</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#dthorn-thorn2009"/>, p. <citedRange>91</citedRange></bibl>.
                    </p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-65296"><name nymRef="#Πεῖσις"><supplied reason="lost">Π</supplied>εῖσι<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied></name>
                    <lb n="2"/><persName type="attested" key="http://clas-lgpn2.classics.ox.ac.uk/cgi-bin/lgpn_search.cgi?id=V1-63471"><name nymRef="#Δᾶμις" type="patronymic">Δάμιος</name></persName></persName>.
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p><app loc="1"><lem><supplied reason="lost">Π</supplied>εῖσι<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied> <note>read from Thorn's drawing</note></lem>
                    <rdg resp="#thorn2005"><supplied reason="lost">Π</supplied>εῖσ<supplied reason="lost">ις</supplied></rdg>
                    <rdg resp="#ghislanzoni1915">Πεῖσις</rdg>
                </app>
                </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="fr" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Peisis fils de Damis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="en" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Peisis son of Damis.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:lang="it" xml:space="preserve">
            <p>Peisis figlio di Damis.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
	           <p>From Ghislanzoni's explanations (no photograph nor drawing) we gather that the stele was found near a sarcophagus and would have stood on top of its lid.</p>
	           <p>The stele is now localised by Thorn, who does approve the relation with one of the nearby sarcophagi.</p>
                <p>Thorn also mentions another stele standing at the same place: <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr029350</ref>.</p>
            </div></body>
    </text>
